+# Root Security Note — AIKIDO-2026-10923 (starlette 0.45.3)
+
+`dummy.patch` is intentionally a **no-op source change**. It adds this note only so the
+`AIKIDO-2026-10923` directory is discovered by the patcher and the scanner ID stays listed
+in `meta.json` / `build.yaml`.
+
+The real fix is applied by the sibling patch directory `CVE-2026-48710/`
+(`CVE-2026-48710.patch`).
+
+## Advisory
+
+| Field | Value |
+|-------|-------|
+| Scanner ID | AIKIDO-2026-10923 |
+| Aliases | CVE-2026-48710, GHSA-86qp-5c8j-p5mr, PYSEC-2026-161 |
+| Package | starlette@0.45.3 |
+| Severity | Critical |
+| Internal ticket | TP-109617 (status: done) |
+| Fixed version | 0.45.3+aikido.14 |
+
+## Why we keep a dummy patch
+
+`AIKIDO-2026-10923` and `CVE-2026-48710` are two identifiers for the same upstream
+advisory: malformed `Host` headers could cause Starlette's `URL` helper to derive a request
+path that differs from `scope["path"]`, enabling cache poisoning and request-smuggling style
+attacks. The fix adds host-header validation in `starlette/datastructures.py`.
+
+Because both identifiers describe the same vulnerability, applying a second copy of the same
+source changes for `AIKIDO-2026-10923` would fail with "Hunk #N FAILED" — the target code has
+already been modified by `CVE-2026-48710.patch`. This dummy patch tracks the Aikido scanner
+ID without re-applying the fix.
+
+## Build-time behaviour
+
+The patcher discovers patch directories under `patches/` and applies any `*.patch` file it
+finds. This patch only adds the present markdown file; listing `AIKIDO-2026-10923` in
+`meta.json` is a metadata claim. The vulnerability is remediated by `CVE-2026-48710.patch`.

